</figure>


<p>
This also helps us understand the meaning of the <alert> phase constant </alert>. The <alert> phase </alert> of the motion is determined by the quantity <m> \phi = \omega t +\phi_0</m> and represents the angle of the particle in circular motion. The phase constant <m> \phi_0 </m>  is the initial angle when <m> t = 0 </m>. Setting <m> t = 0 </m> in our position function for a simple harmonic oscillator, we can find the initial x-position

<me> x_0 = A \cos(\phi_0) </me> 

Thus different values of the phase constant represent different starting points on the circle and correspond to different <em> initial conditions </em> of the motion. 
</p>

